1. First, we start by calculating the depth of the tree using a queue (BFS traversal). For each level, we increment the depth variable. 

2. Then, we initialize the formatted layout matrix (res) as a 2-dimensional array with dimensions m (depth) and n (2^(m) - 1). We fill the matrix with empty strings.

3. After initializing the matrix, we traverse the tree again using the BFS approach and fill in the node values in the matrix accordingly at each level. The position of each node in the current level is based on calculations involving the step value, which is initialized as (1 << (depth - 1)) and divided by 2 before moving to the next level. We add the result of these calculations to the current position.

4. Finally, after the BFS traversal is complete, we return the formatted layout matrix (res).
